        <link:link rdf:resource="#item_826"/>
        <dc:title>The NeuroARTifact Project: Seeing with the Mind</dc:title>
        <dcterms:abstract>The NeuroARTifact project explores the intersection of neuroscience and archaeology, examining how individuals perceive and interact with archaeological artifacts. This study focuses on the Sarcophagus of the Spouses at the National Etruscan Museum in Rome, comparing observers’ experiences in both physical and virtual environments. Using advanced technologies such as electroencephalography (EEG) and eye tracking, the project investigates the cognitive and emotional responses of participants during artifact observation. The research employs visual thinking strategies (VTS) alongside neurophysiological data collection to analyze how people engage with cultural objects. Findings reveal differences in attention patterns and emotional responses between physical and virtual artifact experiences, with the museum environment generally eliciting stronger cognitive and emotional engagement. By integrating neuroscientific methodologies with archaeological research, the NeuroARTifact project opens new avenues for understanding the complex relationship between humans and material culture.</dcterms:abstract>
        <dc:date>2025-08</dc:date>
        <dc:identifier>
            <dcterms:URI>
                <rdf:value>https://doi.org/10.1093/9780197582053.003.0007</rdf:value>
            </dcterms:URI>
        </dc:identifier>
        <dc:description>_eprint: https://academic.oup.com/book/0/chapter/522514305/chapter-pdf/63438449/workid-usac0016834-book-part-7.pdf</dc:description>
    </bib:BookSection>
